Java CC Newsletter 2018 WEEK 38
 
 
 

Steaming Cup of Coffee

 
 
 

JEP Draft: Concise Method Bodies  

The Java language is constantly evolving! Check this feature proposal which will introduce a much simpler syntax for methods declaration similar to lambda expressions. 

 
 
 
 
 

Java Is Still Free 

With the recent changes to Oracle JDK distribution and support, theres been considerable uncertainty over the rights to use Oracle JDK vs Oracle's OpenJDK builds vs OpenJDK builds from other providers. Don't miss the Shorter Version if you haven't heard about the new license model or read the Longer Version if you want to get all the details

 
 
 

Time to Upgrade

 
 
 
 
 
 

Gatling 3.0.0-RC1 

Gatling is a highly capable load testing tool. It is designed to treat your performance tests as production code. Maintenance and automation are made easier. Check its latest release candidate as it comes with some major internals refactorings and features.

 
 
 
 
 

Spring Framework 5.1.0 

Spring Framework 5.1 requires JDK 8 or higher and specifically supports JDK 11 as the next long-term support release. It comes with initial refinements for GraalVM compatibility and deeply integrates with the recently released Reactor Californium and Hibernate ORM 5.3. Try it out!

 
 

There Is Always More to Learn

 
 
 
 

Get the Java Magazine! 

Ready to dive deeply into Java and JVM once again with Java Magazine? Explore the contents of its latest issue as it includes tutorials on new technologies, investigations of alternative JVM languages, explanations of important tools, and lots of advice on coding. 

 
 
 
 

The Ultimate Guide to the Java Stream API groupingBy() Collector 

Still a bit puzzled by what the groupingBy() collector can do in the Java Stream API? Check out this guide on using the groupingBy() collector to its fullest potential.

 
 
 
 
 
 
 

23 Guidelines for Writing Readable Code 

Reading someone else's code can be quite confusing. Hours can go on issues that should have been fixed in minutes. In this article, you are going to hunt some really good advices on how to write code that will be easier to understand and maintain. 

 
 
 
 

How to Query by Entity Type Using JPA Criteria API 

The JPA Criteria API provides an alternative way for defining JPA queries, which is mainly useful for building dynamic queries whose exact structure is only known at runtime. Take a deep dive into the Criteria API and check how you can filter by the entity type.

 
 
 
 
 

Spring Boot integration in IntelliJ IDEA 

If youre developing with Spring Boot, IntelliJ IDEA does offer a lot more niceties to speed up development time. Lets browse through some of them to help you increase your productivity! 

 
 
 
 

An Introduction to Spring Batch 

Want to learn more about using Spring Batch to run large amounts of data on your application? Read more to learn more in this post on Spring Batch using Quartz.

 
 
 
 
 
 

Java Home Made Face Recognition Application 

As a Java Developer you are probably eager to learn more about Deep Learning and its applications, but you might not feel like learning another language at the moment. Are you facing lack of the support or confusion with Machine Learning and Java? This resource can be of a great help to you in making the journey with deep learning an exciting experience.

 
 
 
 

JDBC in Java, Hibernate, and ORMs:
The Ultimate Resource 

As a Java developer, its very likely youll need to connect to a database. 
This article is a great starting point to get the big picture in how to manage persistence in Java and what the available technologies are.
It also offers an amazing set of resources for further reading so dont miss it!

 
 
 
 
 

Functional Programming in Java With Vavr 

Vavr is a super cool library which gives you a lot of features, that turn Java into a real functional programming language. Lets take a look at the super powerful tools like Option, Tuple, Try, Collections and Pattern Matching! 

 
 
 
 
 

Setting Up Static Code Analysis for Java  

Why is static code analysis important? It helps us to ensure the overall code quality, to fix bugs in early stage of development and to ensure that each developer is using the same coding standards when writing the code. Lets go through a basic setup of static code analysis for a Java project!

 
 
 
 
 
 

JUnit 5 Extension Model: How To Create Your Own Extensions 

We already know quite a lot about JUnit 5. Lets now examine Jupiters extension model, which allows third parties to extend JUnit.Thats not only pretty cool if you are implementing libraries and frameworks, but also very useful for you as application developer because you can adapt JUnit 5 to your projects specific traits.
